definition.value: A compound used to form the matrix for MALDI (matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization) mass spectrometry. MALDI matrix materials are crystalline compounds with a fairly low molecular weight, so as to allow facile vaporization, have strong absorption at UV or IR wavelengths (to rapidly and efficiently absorb laser irradiation), generally contain polar groups (enabling them to be used in aqueous solutions) and are frequently acidic (so assisting ionisation of the compound being studied, which is contained within the matrix material).
A neurotransmitter transporter modulator that activates glutamate transporters.
A membrane transport modulator that affects the transport of neurotransmitters.
An excitatory amino acid agonist which binds to NMDA receptors and triggers a response.
A food additive which is added to flour or dough to improve baking quality and/or colour.
The role played by a substance in enhancing the appearance or odour of the human body; a name given to the substance itself or to a component of it.

A drug used to treat or prevent infections caused by Mycobacteria, a genus of actinobacteria. Aerobic and nonmotile, members of the genus include the pathogens responsible for causing tuberculosis and leprosy.
An antiparasitic drug which is effective against Apicomplexan parasites in the genus Plasmodium. The genus contains over 200 species and includes those responsible for malaria.
A depigmentation agent which inhibits the synthesis of melanin.
Any compound that has anti-asthmatic effects.

Antipsychotic drugs which can have different modes of action but which tend to be more likely than second generation antipsychotics to cause extrapyramidal motor control disabilities such as body rigidity or Parkinson's disease-type movements; such body movements can become permanent even after treatment has ceased.

Antipsychotic drugs which can have different modes of action but which tend to be less likely than first generation antipsychotics to cause extrapyramidal motor control disabilities such as body rigidity or Parkinson's disease-type movements.
Substances which are added to food in order to prevent decomposition caused by  microbial growth or by undesirable chemical changes.

A food preservative which prevents decomposition of food by preventing the growth of fungi or bacteria. In European countries, E-numbers for permitted food preservatives are from E200 to E299, divided into sorbates (E200-209), benzoates (E210-219), sulfites (E220-229), phenols and formates (E230-239), nitrates (E240-259), acetates (E260-269), lactates (E270-279), propionates (E280-289) and others (E290-299).
A compound that inhibits the action of gamma-aminobutyric acid.
Any substance which is used to neutralise stomach acidity.
Any compound which can be used to treat or alleviate the symptoms of dyskinesia.
Any compound that improves mental functions such as cognition, memory, intelligence, motivation, attention, and concentration.
Any compound used for the treatment of eye conditions or eye diseases.
Any compound that is able to protect normal cells from the damage caused by radiation therapy.
Any compound which inhibits the postganglionic functioning of the sympathetic nervous system (SNS).
Any compound used to suppress premature labour and immature birth by suppressing uterine contractions.
Any compound that has anti-inflammatory effects.
A chemosterilant intended to sterilize insects.
A reagent used in the determination of the concentration of a coloured chemical element or chemical compound in solution.
In NMR spectroscopy a reagent added to a solution to induce chemical shifts and thus simplify complex spectra.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates a retinoic acid receptor.
A hormone agonist that binds to and activates progesterone receptors.
An antiprotozoal drug used to treat or prevent infections caused by protozoan parasites that belong to the genus Leishmania.
Any entity used to generate reactive oxygen species.
A hormone receptor modulator that acts as a complete or partial agonist or as an antagonist at the progesterone receptor.
Any drug that has been developed specifically for treatment of a rare medical condition, the condition itself being known as an orphan disease.
A histamine agonist that binds to and activates H1-receptors.
An insecticide that acts as a repellent to insects.
Any molecule shown to have the potentiality in stimulating the effect of nerve growth factor.
Any compound that promotes the growth of new blood vessels from pre-existing vessels.
Any compound that protects plants by activating their defence mechanisms.
A hormone antagonist that inhibits the action of the peptide hormone cholecystokinin.
An acaricide that kills mites of the genus Sarcoptes.
A hormone agonist that binds to and activates a thyroid hormone receptor.
A drug used in treating and healing of wounds.
Any agent used to determine the amino-acid sequence in a polypeptide.
A reagent used in the determination by spectrophotometry of the concentration of a chemical element or chemical compound in solution.
A reagent used to couple amino acids during artificial peptide synthesis.
Substance used to set dyes on fabrics or tissue sections by forming a coordination complex with the dye which then attaches to the fabric or tissue.
A role borne by a molecule that acts to counteract or neutralize the deleterious effects of paracetamol (acetaminophen).
A role borne by a molecule that acts to counteract or neutralize the deleterious effects of curare.
A compound that causes the contraction of body tissues, typically used to reduce bleeding from minor abrasions.
A compound used as a probe during microarray analysis of oligosaccharide-protein interactions.
A reagent used in the immobilization of compounds prior to their use in microarray analysis.
